1
00:00:00,149 --> 00:00:17,853
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodassam Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodassam

2
00:00:18,442 --> 00:00:27,638
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhutassa.

3
00:00:27,658 --> 00:00:31,545
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

4
00:00:39,319 --> 00:00:40,921
The last talk I was...

5
00:00:41,475 --> 00:00:58,862
talking about the way our cultural way of looking at things through science or scientism and through our romantic understanding of life and through psychotherapy tends to distort the teaching of the Buddha.

6
00:00:59,524 --> 00:01:05,533
And I boiled it down, this teaching, I boiled it down to ethics and transcendence.

7
00:01:05,552 --> 00:01:08,277
So...

8
00:01:08,932 --> 00:01:19,043
If you look at what's happening from a science point of view, it's easy to understand that you're looking upwards through matter.

9
00:01:19,703 --> 00:01:26,510
And matter sort of begins to create chemicals, chemicals, some sort of bio-life.

10
00:01:26,930 --> 00:01:34,399
And so it all looks very clear, that consciousness and all that appears as part of that process, that upward process of evolution.

11
00:01:34,885 --> 00:01:43,039
So it's quite understandable that that would make sense to somebody brought up in that sort of scientific tradition.

12
00:01:43,840 --> 00:01:56,382
If you're not, of course, if you've been brought up in a religious tradition, one of the Christian traditions or Islam or Judaism or Hinduism, then, of course, you're looking at it from a slightly different way.

13
00:01:56,441 --> 00:01:57,763
You're looking at it down.

14
00:01:57,823 --> 00:01:58,986
You're looking down.

15
00:01:58,965 --> 00:02:03,072
and seeing how everything slowly descends to the material base.

16
00:02:03,772 --> 00:02:07,459
So that's what I want to try and do this evening, to give you a different perspective.

17
00:02:08,441 --> 00:02:14,770
And the first thing is to be clear about what the Buddha means by transcendence, what he's pointing to.

18
00:02:14,811 --> 00:02:19,016
So in the last talk I also mentioned some of these.

19
00:02:19,451 --> 00:02:45,139
quotes the one where people feel that he's been most clear is this one it says there is a sphere or a dimension where there's no earth no water no fire no air now those of course are your four great elements by which the mind contacts matter okay so when you're looking at the pain in your knees it'll either be fiery

20
00:02:45,997 --> 00:02:47,759
Or it'll be heavy and thick.

21
00:02:49,644 --> 00:02:58,661
So remember that when the Buddha talks about the world, the all, he's not talking about the objective world of science.

22
00:02:58,681 --> 00:03:02,127
He's talking about the way we experience it.

23
00:03:02,146 --> 00:03:04,831
The world that we're actually manufacturing.

24
00:03:05,352 --> 00:03:07,175
He's always talking from that angle.

25
00:03:07,616 --> 00:03:17,437
It's not that he denies that the world out there exists, but he's saying that from the point of view of liberation, it's the world that we're actually creating that we've got to be liberated from.

26
00:03:20,185 --> 00:03:26,897
And he says there's no base consisting of space, consciousness, nothingness, perception, non-perception.

27
00:03:27,879 --> 00:03:35,074
This refers to these higher jhanic states, which is the most refined place that the mind can get to, you see.

28
00:03:35,616 --> 00:03:41,366
It's when the mind actually stops producing, and there's just the awareness of that space, etc.,

29
00:03:42,275 --> 00:03:47,580
And then he says it's neither this world or another world, nor both, neither sun nor moon.

30
00:03:47,661 --> 00:03:54,127
So he is saying that there isn't a physical world where this transcendent place is.

31
00:03:54,147 --> 00:03:56,870
He says there's no coming and going and no staying.

32
00:03:57,211 --> 00:04:00,814
So there's no sense of space and there's no sense of time.

33
00:04:01,455 --> 00:04:03,317
There's no ceasing, no uprising.

34
00:04:03,538 --> 00:04:05,539
So it's without change.

35
00:04:06,039 --> 00:04:07,741
This place is without change.

36
00:04:08,312 --> 00:04:12,058
So remember those three characteristics, dukkha, anicca and atta.

37
00:04:12,098 --> 00:04:14,643
So there's no suffering there, it's adukkha.

38
00:04:15,104 --> 00:04:18,208
There's no impermanence there, it's nicca.

39
00:04:18,869 --> 00:04:21,452
And of course there's no self there, there's no sense of a self.

40
00:04:21,574 --> 00:04:25,038
It's a non-dual state.

41
00:04:26,199 --> 00:04:28,463
It's not fixed, it's not movable.

42
00:04:29,064 --> 00:04:30,745
So it's not fixed and it's not movable.

43
00:04:31,026 --> 00:04:32,767
So it's not fixed and movable.

44
00:04:32,908 --> 00:04:39,456
It's coming from our position that everything has a place and you can move most things, right?

45
00:04:39,576 --> 00:04:40,478
Everything changes.

46
00:04:41,038 --> 00:04:41,959
But there, there's nothing.

47
00:04:42,220 --> 00:04:45,624
So you can't talk about something being fixed or movable.

48
00:04:46,545 --> 00:04:48,367
And it has no support.

49
00:04:49,148 --> 00:04:50,470
So this means...

50
00:04:51,276 --> 00:04:54,480
Everything in this world is dependent on something else.

51
00:04:54,940 --> 00:04:56,762
Nothing arises of itself.

52
00:04:56,783 --> 00:04:58,064
There's no existent.

53
00:05:00,266 --> 00:05:06,252
But this is a place where it doesn't need anything at all.

54
00:05:06,552 --> 00:05:13,079
So he's obviously pointing to something which is quite other than what we're experiencing.

55
00:05:13,100 --> 00:05:15,882
And that's what we mean by transcendence.

56
00:05:17,584 --> 00:05:19,107
And he says, just this is the end of suffering.

57
00:05:19,627 --> 00:05:25,355
So then, of course, there's the other famous one that people quote.

58
00:05:25,375 --> 00:05:32,964
There exists, so the word ati, there is the not born, the not compounded, the not created, the not conditioned.

59
00:05:33,346 --> 00:05:41,716
But then he goes on to a second verse which he says, if there were not this not born, not compounded, not created, not conditioned, there'd be no escape.

60
00:05:42,598 --> 00:05:46,021
No escape could be discerned from the born, the compounded,

61
00:05:46,237 --> 00:05:47,560
the created and the conditioned.

62
00:05:50,286 --> 00:05:55,478
And then the final verse says, but because there is this not born, then there is obviously an escape.

63
00:05:56,221 --> 00:06:03,538
So again, he's talking about something which is of another nature, you might say, another dimension.

64
00:06:05,526 --> 00:06:12,639
And the other final one which I brought up the last time was this question of where do earth, water, fire and air find no footing?

65
00:06:12,738 --> 00:06:15,423
Remember, somebody asks him where the world comes to an end.

66
00:06:15,523 --> 00:06:16,884
So this is the world we're creating.

67
00:06:16,904 --> 00:06:19,329
And he says, well, that's the wrong question.

68
00:06:19,369 --> 00:06:21,713
You should ask where does it find no footing?

69
00:06:21,973 --> 00:06:24,057
So there's nothing destroyed in the process.

70
00:06:24,877 --> 00:06:30,326
He himself says the only thing that's destroyed in the process of liberation is greed, hatred and delusion.

71
00:06:30,608 --> 00:06:32,630
Everything else remains.

72
00:06:36,829 --> 00:06:39,552
Where are long and short, small, fair, foul?

73
00:06:40,514 --> 00:06:44,238
Where are the subject and object wholly destroyed, you see?

74
00:06:45,321 --> 00:06:47,103
A sense of object.

75
00:06:47,302 --> 00:06:49,004
Remember this non-dual place.

76
00:06:51,108 --> 00:06:57,014
If you say there's one, there's a presumption that there may be a two, right?

77
00:06:57,247 --> 00:06:59,711
So that's why this word of non-dual is coined.

78
00:07:00,372 --> 00:07:03,495
But of course each system has a different understanding of non-dual.

79
00:07:04,016 --> 00:07:08,682
So for the Hindus, non-dual, the non-dual state is to be at one with Brahman.

80
00:07:10,223 --> 00:07:14,288
But in the Buddhist tradition, it's to be in this state of nibbana.

81
00:07:16,992 --> 00:07:20,016
So he says that there is a consciousness which is non-manifestive.

82
00:07:21,278 --> 00:07:27,644
Now a consciousness that's manifestive is manifesting through the six senses.

83
00:07:27,665 --> 00:07:30,827
The five basic physical senses and the mind.

84
00:07:31,509 --> 00:07:35,031
Mind, heart, emotions and thoughts.

85
00:07:35,492 --> 00:07:36,774
So he said it's non-manifestive.

86
00:07:36,814 --> 00:07:37,875
So it's without boundary.

87
00:07:38,495 --> 00:07:41,459
So boundaries are created by phenomena, by objects, by things.

88
00:07:42,079 --> 00:07:42,901
So there's nothing there.

89
00:07:42,961 --> 00:07:43,680
That's what he's saying.

90
00:07:44,661 --> 00:07:46,223
And it's all directions full of light.

91
00:07:46,845 --> 00:07:47,185
So consciousness.

92
00:07:47,670 --> 00:07:58,901
You can take that as either a state of light or a brightness as if you were inside the bulb, or you can take it as a state of pure awareness.

93
00:08:00,403 --> 00:08:06,689
And he says here's where this earth, water, fire and air, so the physical nature, our physical nature, finds no footing.

94
00:08:08,271 --> 00:08:14,158
He says it's where all these opposites, long and short, small and great and so on, subjects and objects are wholly destroyed.

95
00:08:14,757 --> 00:08:16,259
They don't exist there.

96
00:08:20,459 --> 00:08:28,968
Okay, so now we have this, if we keep the idea of something that's transcendent, right?

97
00:08:28,988 --> 00:08:32,212
Now, what doesn't the Buddha talk about?

98
00:08:32,552 --> 00:08:34,975
What won't he actually talk about?

99
00:08:34,995 --> 00:08:39,881
So there were these ten questions that were, I suppose, the obsessions of the age, really.

100
00:08:40,682 --> 00:08:42,325
So the first one is, is the world eternal?

101
00:08:42,424 --> 00:08:43,907
Is the world not eternal?

102
00:08:43,927 --> 00:08:44,788
Is the world infinite?

103
00:08:44,908 --> 00:08:48,491
Is the world finite?

104
00:08:48,623 --> 00:08:50,407
Is the soul the same as the body?

105
00:08:50,748 --> 00:08:55,217
So if it is, then you would be an annihilationist because when the body dies, you go as well.

106
00:08:56,900 --> 00:09:00,087
Soul here would be your body and mind, your mind rather.

107
00:09:00,809 --> 00:09:03,215
And is the soul different from the body?

108
00:09:03,235 --> 00:09:07,644
In which case, the soul would separate from the body and you'd be an eternalist.

109
00:09:08,772 --> 00:09:11,695
So there were these two opposites at the time of the Buddha.

110
00:09:11,754 --> 00:09:22,504
You've got the Brahmins and the Jains who said the soul was released, the Jiva was released into a heavenly state or at one with Brahman.

111
00:09:23,166 --> 00:09:25,528
And there were the materialists who said, you know, that was it.

112
00:09:25,827 --> 00:09:26,668
When you're dead, you're dead.

113
00:09:27,909 --> 00:09:30,952
And then the last four were concerning somebody who was fully liberated.

114
00:09:31,533 --> 00:09:35,857
So does the Tathagat exist after death or does he not exist?

115
00:09:36,538 --> 00:09:38,019
And then this...

116
00:09:38,590 --> 00:09:40,272
Does he exist and not exist?

117
00:09:40,711 --> 00:09:43,956
And then finally, does he neither exist nor not exist?

118
00:09:45,476 --> 00:09:51,523
So he's cornered any sort of effort at rational... Well, of course, he's silent, you see.

119
00:09:52,965 --> 00:09:56,889
And he's silent because the questions are always coming from the point of view of a self.

120
00:09:57,408 --> 00:09:59,311
And this is what he says to Vatsya, you see.

121
00:09:59,951 --> 00:10:01,714
And then he says his usual thing.

122
00:10:01,734 --> 00:10:02,894
He says his feeling.

123
00:10:03,235 --> 00:10:07,720
He says they regard feeling as self, perception as self, volitional formations as self,

124
00:10:07,902 --> 00:10:37,081
consciousness as self or self as possessing consciousness or consciousness is in self or self as in consciousness therefore when the wanderers of other sects ask such questions they give such answers the world is eternal they can be very certain about it but the thing is that he never actually says anything about it he doesn't make any he doesn't give any indication as to whether it is or not

125
00:10:37,466 --> 00:10:47,282
You know, even he might sort of say, well, for those who don't have a self, there is an eternal, etc., etc.

126
00:10:47,782 --> 00:10:49,845
But he just goes, he just goes, mum.

127
00:10:56,235 --> 00:11:04,486
So when it comes to those sorts of questions about the world and things like that, he's quite...

128
00:11:04,822 --> 00:11:06,885
he doesn't go there.

129
00:11:07,326 --> 00:11:08,929
But we'll come to something else in a minute.

130
00:11:10,173 --> 00:11:11,075
We'll come back to that.

131
00:11:12,256 --> 00:11:24,402
The next thing that, you know, you might ask, we might ask, but it never, doesn't seem to occur in the scriptures is, why does this occur in the first place?

132
00:11:24,562 --> 00:11:25,884
You know, like, where does this

133
00:11:26,388 --> 00:11:54,859
satipanya or as the abhidharma would put it this nibhanic element in us or as the mahayana would point to it as say buddha nature where does it come from why has it come here where did it all begin so those sorts of questions the relationship of this nibhanadhatu and how it's come here again it's never broached I don't know of a question that comes up in the scriptures to do with that

134
00:11:55,682 --> 00:12:04,815
And it's the same with the relationship that our individual, inverted commas, Nibbanadhatus have with each other.

135
00:12:05,235 --> 00:12:16,610
So presumably there's lots of Arahants whose Nibbanadhatus, this element, this Buddha nature, is somewhere and do they communicate?

136
00:12:16,912 --> 00:12:17,913
Do they communicate?

137
00:12:17,953 --> 00:12:25,004
Do they know whether, you know, the last perfectly enlightened person is next door or upstairs?

138
00:12:26,365 --> 00:12:29,331
So all that area, it just doesn't come up for discussion.

139
00:12:29,510 --> 00:12:31,092
It just doesn't arise, you see.

140
00:12:36,682 --> 00:12:41,249
But, of course, other, like the Hindus, you know, tried to work something out for that.

141
00:12:42,129 --> 00:12:43,392
And so...

142
00:12:43,539 --> 00:12:56,457
as you become liberated in the Hindu tradition, where you get moksha, freedom, of course, your atta, your self, inverted commas, big self, goes back into brahman.

143
00:12:56,477 --> 00:12:57,980
You become brahman, you see.

144
00:12:58,701 --> 00:13:11,639
So, in that sense, you've got this idea that brahman, who's neuter, by the way, he's neither male nor female, bursts into all these different attas, and then they've got to find their way back to him.

145
00:13:12,110 --> 00:13:18,677
So in other words, they're trying to answer this question, but it never comes up in the scriptures.

146
00:13:19,817 --> 00:13:21,519
And the Buddha never approaches it.

147
00:13:22,780 --> 00:13:25,724
So that's the end of that.

148
00:13:28,225 --> 00:13:36,615
So it's just knowing that Buddhism doesn't have a monopoly on all truth, that's all.

149
00:13:38,788 --> 00:13:42,474
Now, some would say that they're known as avyākata questions.

150
00:13:42,534 --> 00:13:44,297
Avyākata just means not determined.

151
00:13:44,537 --> 00:13:47,260
So he's just not spoken about it.

152
00:13:47,721 --> 00:13:51,287
But maybe there's something that is forever unknowable.

153
00:13:52,089 --> 00:13:57,797
You know, just to be able to accept that these sorts of questions are actually unknowable.

154
00:13:58,538 --> 00:14:06,669
And that may be one reason why the Buddha kept himself strictly to this particular teaching of liberation.

155
00:14:07,357 --> 00:14:17,090
He does say in one place where he points to the person he's with and he says, or to the monks he's with, he says, you see all the leaves in this forest.

156
00:14:18,030 --> 00:14:25,880
He says, well, I know, it's like I know all this, but I've only given you a clump of leaves which you need in order to be liberated.

157
00:14:27,081 --> 00:14:29,043
Because you don't know where that was put in later, you see.

158
00:14:31,447 --> 00:14:36,994
Because in the, thank heavens it doesn't say it in the scriptures, but in the...

159
00:14:37,767 --> 00:14:50,423
In the Visuddhimagga, which is the medieval work of a Buddha dasa, they describe the qualities of a Buddha, by which time, of course, he's grown to this sort of superhuman, you know, just amazing, beyond human.

160
00:14:51,083 --> 00:14:54,668
And they say that he's omniscient.

161
00:14:55,409 --> 00:14:59,495
What they mean by that is if he bends his mind towards anything, he'll know the answer.

162
00:14:59,855 --> 00:15:01,878
And one thing he knows is that the world is flat.

163
00:15:03,519 --> 00:15:04,360
That's a killer, isn't it?

164
00:15:05,101 --> 00:15:06,423
So you say, okay.

165
00:15:08,664 --> 00:15:14,591
So you have to recognise that there's some, you know, messing about here.

166
00:15:16,313 --> 00:15:20,099
So, OK, so that's something he doesn't talk about.

167
00:15:21,379 --> 00:15:27,967
And just to go back a step in a way, just to the origins of the universe, again, there's no effort to do that.

168
00:15:27,988 --> 00:15:35,937
There is this peculiar discourse, the Aganya Sutta, in which he lays out a certain...

169
00:15:37,318 --> 00:15:49,557
creation myth but it's obviously a satire I mean most people see it now as a satire it starts off with him having a talk with this man called Vatsita

170
00:15:50,514 --> 00:15:54,802
Once the Lord was staying at Stabati at the mansion of Migara's mother in the East Park.

171
00:15:54,822 --> 00:16:00,331
And at that time, Vasata and Bharadvaja were living among monks, hoping to become monks themselves.

172
00:16:00,390 --> 00:16:06,861
And in the evening, the Lord rose from his secluded meditation and came out of the mansion, started walking up and down in the shade.

173
00:16:07,462 --> 00:16:12,650
Vasata noticed this and he said to Bharadvaja, Friend, Bharadvaja, the Lord has come out and is walking up and down.

174
00:16:12,691 --> 00:16:13,613
Let's go and approach him.

175
00:16:14,114 --> 00:16:17,298
We might be fortunate enough to hear a talk on Dhamma with the Lord himself.

176
00:16:17,514 --> 00:16:19,357
Yes, indeed, said Bharavadja.

177
00:16:19,378 --> 00:16:22,261
And they went up to the Lord, saluted him and fell into step with him.

178
00:16:23,283 --> 00:16:35,501
And then the Lord said to Vasudha, Vasudha, you two are Brahmins born and bred and you have gone forth to the house from household life to the homeless life from Brahmin families.

179
00:16:35,761 --> 00:16:37,784
Do not the Brahmins revile and abuse you?

180
00:16:39,823 --> 00:16:42,048
Indeed, Lord, the Brahmins do revile abusers.

181
00:16:42,089 --> 00:16:44,653
They don't hold back with their usual flood of reproaches.

182
00:16:46,076 --> 00:16:47,961
What kind of reproaches do they fling at you?

183
00:16:48,601 --> 00:16:51,969
Lord, what the Brahmin says is that the Brahmin caste is the highest caste.

184
00:16:51,989 --> 00:16:53,032
Other castes are base.

185
00:16:53,152 --> 00:16:54,374
The Brahmin caste is fair.

186
00:16:54,475 --> 00:16:55,496
Other castes are dark.

187
00:16:55,596 --> 00:16:56,759
Brahmins are purified.

188
00:16:56,860 --> 00:16:58,001
Non-Brahmin's are not.

189
00:16:58,488 --> 00:17:06,701
The Brahmins are the true children of Brahma, born of the mouth of Brahma, created by Brahma, heirs of Brahma.

190
00:17:06,721 --> 00:17:15,575
And you, you've deserted the highest caste and gone over to the base caste, these shaveling, petty ascetics, servant, dark fellows, born of the Brahma's foot.

191
00:17:17,298 --> 00:17:20,563
It's not right, it's not proper that you should mix with such people.

192
00:17:21,691 --> 00:17:23,513
So this is the way the Brahmins abuse us, Lord.

193
00:17:23,773 --> 00:17:38,176
Then faster tell the Brahmins have forgotten their ancient tradition when they say that, because we can see Brahmin women, the wives of Brahmins, who menstruate and become pregnant, have babies and give suck, and yet these womb-born Brahmins talk about being born of the Brahma's mouth.

194
00:17:38,837 --> 00:17:41,382
These Brahmins misrepresent Brahma.

195
00:17:41,402 --> 00:17:42,303
They tell lies.

196
00:17:42,363 --> 00:17:43,986
They earn much demerit.

197
00:17:44,303 --> 00:17:48,907
And then he goes into exactly what happens at the end of the world.

198
00:17:49,489 --> 00:17:55,134
So at the end of the world, you can't have all beings destroyed because then that would be the end of karma.

199
00:17:55,154 --> 00:17:58,699
And it would suggest that some beings are just not going to make it.

200
00:17:59,380 --> 00:18:06,548
So at the end of a world cycle, everybody gets shunted into this highest realm, the Abhasa Brahma, you see.

201
00:18:07,209 --> 00:18:11,233
And of course, there were questions asked about this by later commentators.

202
00:18:11,253 --> 00:18:11,993
How could this be?

203
00:18:12,013 --> 00:18:12,555
You know, because...

204
00:18:12,535 --> 00:18:24,469
to get up there you've got to be in the highest of jhanas and be pretty pure so the um the explanation was that everybody's been around this samsara so many times that they must have hit

205
00:18:25,359 --> 00:18:31,669
one of these Jhanic states, and the good karma would come just at that moment and they'd be up in the Avastra realm.

206
00:18:33,332 --> 00:18:42,164
And this, of course, saved this whole idea of realms from bringing an end to karma.

207
00:18:42,605 --> 00:18:51,960
