So the purgatorial realm, which is sometimes called hell realm.

398
00:39:57,052 --> 00:40:04,141
But hell, you know, according to Dante, I mean, that's, you know, abandon all hope, you enter here.

399
00:40:04,541 --> 00:40:05,041
So...

400
00:40:05,291 --> 00:40:18,342
There's nothing eternal in the world, according to Buddhism, so it's much better to think of it as purgatory, where you purge your sins and get rid of all your bad karma.

401
00:40:21,186 --> 00:40:31,875
And there are various levels of that, the worst one being the Avicii hell, of course, where those who've been extremely cruel go, which is the opposite of the Buddhist teaching about compassion, of course.

402
00:40:32,876 --> 00:40:34,016
Then there's the animal realm,

403
00:40:34,351 --> 00:40:36,273
You see, born an animal.

404
00:40:36,293 --> 00:40:37,737
There's the human realm, which is ours.

405
00:40:39,139 --> 00:40:41,864
The hungry ghosts, they're the ones who are driven by greed.

406
00:40:42,485 --> 00:40:48,235
There's the angry devas, they're the clever people who are driven by anger, jealousy, all that sort of stuff.

407
00:40:48,715 --> 00:40:51,280
And then finally there's the deva realm, which is where...

408
00:40:51,817 --> 00:40:52,697
People are happy.

409
00:40:53,298 --> 00:40:54,059
Beings are happy.

410
00:40:55,661 --> 00:40:57,121
So you've got these six realms.

411
00:40:57,163 --> 00:41:06,853
And of course, what tends to happen is the relationship between what we experience as human beings extended into other realms of existence.

412
00:41:07,512 --> 00:41:16,001
So if you're in a deep depression and you don't see a way out of it, you're despairing, you're obviously in a hell realm.

413
00:41:17,585 --> 00:41:21,277
If you get drunk and do all sorts of daft things, then you're obviously in an animal realm.

414
00:41:22,079 --> 00:41:23,344
There's the human realm, of course.

415
00:41:23,465 --> 00:41:29,164
When we're craving for stuff and we can't just stop going for those biscuits, then you're a hungry ghost.

416
00:41:29,548 --> 00:41:34,615
And when we're getting angry and trying to get the best of somebody, we're in the angry Deva realm.

417
00:41:35,056 --> 00:41:43,068
And then finally when we're happy and peaceful and wandering about the meadows here, then we're in the Deva realm.

418
00:41:43,088 --> 00:41:50,257
So there's always that connection between what we as human beings can experience and the cosmology that...

419
00:41:50,844 --> 00:42:15,586
that buddhism talks about so those are your basic things but in the abhidhamma it gets much more refined because then they talk about all these various realms to do with also with the jhanas so the whole cosmology is built up into this huge sort of idea of vast of different realms many realms all over the place whether they exist or not is a moot point of course

420
00:42:19,836 --> 00:42:24,121
So in order to get into these realms, of course, you've got to be reborn.

421
00:42:24,682 --> 00:42:26,644
You can't annihilate.

422
00:42:27,346 --> 00:42:28,947
If you annihilate, you don't get reborn.

423
00:42:29,168 --> 00:42:32,130
And therefore, you'll never experience these realms.

424
00:42:32,652 --> 00:42:43,324
So when it comes to rebirth, which is very difficult for us, because if you've been brought up a Christian or a Muslim or something like that, then it's easier.

425
00:42:43,784 --> 00:42:47,329
But for people who've been brought up in a more...

426
00:42:48,119 --> 00:42:56,012
secular way, it's very difficult to actually, you know, just open up to the idea.

427
00:42:57,894 --> 00:42:59,177
There's been lots of studies on it.

428
00:42:59,358 --> 00:43:01,722
I mean, there's, what's his name?

429
00:43:03,965 --> 00:43:07,751
Ian Stevenson has wrote 20 cases suggesting a reincarnation.

430
00:43:08,192 --> 00:43:09,775
And there's also stuff on the website.

431
00:43:10,275 --> 00:43:14,041
I've actually put a clip on our website

432
00:43:15,557 --> 00:43:19,844
So there's no way it's ever going to be proven scientifically.

433
00:43:20,266 --> 00:43:25,773
There's not going to be an fMRI scan of somebody being reborn.

434
00:43:26,735 --> 00:43:34,949
In the medieval ages, they would weigh a body before it died and then weigh it again after it died to see how much the soul weighed.

435
00:43:35,108 --> 00:43:37,592
And they were always upset because it didn't have any weight.

436
00:43:37,612 --> 00:43:38,594
There was no change.

437
00:43:39,199 --> 00:43:43,204
We're trying to prove that something which is transcendent actually exists.

438
00:43:43,585 --> 00:43:48,070
So we can forget about trying to prove whether there's rebirth or not.

439
00:43:48,590 --> 00:43:54,456
But one thing is for sure, that when you start reading the discourses, it comes across all the time.

440
00:43:55,197 --> 00:44:01,405
You can't read the discourses without including rebirth.

441
00:44:01,864 --> 00:44:04,228
They begin to...

442
00:44:05,001 --> 00:44:27,650
they don't make sense in terms of the whole law of karma so even in the Buddha's awakening we talk about the three knowledges that came to him where he remembered his past lives which showed him how he came to be fully liberated and what was the driving force of that was his ethics

443
00:44:27,630 --> 00:44:32,898
And then he saw other beings moving from realm to realm, driven again by their ethics.

444
00:44:33,338 --> 00:44:37,644
So what had been just a personal law, he saw as a universal law.

445
00:44:38,806 --> 00:44:46,697
And then, of course, the third knowledge was that he himself was purified of all his defilements.

446
00:44:47,438 --> 00:44:53,588
So he goes right back to the, in the tradition, it's right back there to the awakening of the whole thing about rebirth.

447
00:44:55,255 --> 00:45:02,943
And there's... Bhikkhu Bodhi has written a sort of monograph on it.

448
00:45:03,623 --> 00:45:06,365
And I've taken his ideas from there.

449
00:45:07,106 --> 00:45:10,990
And the question he asks is, well, does it make sense?

450
00:45:11,170 --> 00:45:12,311
Is it intelligible?

451
00:45:13,873 --> 00:45:16,076
Does it make any sense in terms of the Dharma?

452
00:45:16,836 --> 00:45:24,704
Well, you can see that without the idea of rebirth, how do you ever resolve...

453
00:45:24,836 --> 00:45:39,757
the actions that you've made and this also moves into the idea that the universe has some sort of moral equilibrium has some sort of moral resolution to it

454
00:45:39,922 --> 00:45:54,760
You might say that's more of an intuitive thing, that eventually whatever harm somebody has done has to be mended in some way, has to be ameliorated, has to be compensated for.

455
00:45:55,101 --> 00:45:57,746
So you have to forget the idea of punishment.

456
00:45:57,827 --> 00:45:59,791
It's to do with results.

457
00:46:00,291 --> 00:46:06,059
You do something wrong and there will be a result within your psychophysical organism.

458
00:46:06,739 --> 00:46:16,030
And the result will reverberate back to this Buddha nature when it wakens up and realises, oh, I've done something wrong.

459
00:46:16,431 --> 00:46:24,983
I'm now in a world, my world, the world I'm creating, which is full of guilt, full of remorse, full of shame.

460
00:46:25,132 --> 00:46:46,498
see and of course the world then mirrors back to you so if you're very sarcastic you find yourself you know being a bit lonely sometimes so the way you behave also affects other people and they mirror your behavior back to you by the way they behave towards you so um

461
00:46:46,882 --> 00:47:00,043
There's a feeling that there must be some work out, because as we know, in the ordinary world as we see it, people get away with murder, and people who do wonderful things are never acknowledged.

462
00:47:00,983 --> 00:47:02,586
They might end up in a bad way too.

463
00:47:03,067 --> 00:47:14,864
Remember that poor man who went out to help the business in the Middle East, and they caught him and they shot him out in the desert somewhere.

464
00:47:15,284 --> 00:47:39,891
jihadi john one of the isis people do you remember that awful thing he'd gone out on a to help a muslim charity and he got out to the east you might remember it and he and they he was up on youtube and he you know they showed him on youtube and just before he was to be shot so there's you know that and that makes you think well you know how does that how does that work out you know

465
00:47:41,795 --> 00:47:51,353
Some people think that just because you're born or you go through something terrible in this life, that this is because you did something terrible in the past life.

466
00:47:57,003 --> 00:48:01,693
I think you've heard me talk about this tale which comes up in the...

467
00:48:02,820 --> 00:48:07,485
In the Dharmapada, where there's a ship going across the ocean and it suddenly stops.

468
00:48:07,565 --> 00:48:08,385
It doesn't move.

469
00:48:08,927 --> 00:48:13,490
And the captain goes and consults these monks who are on board.

470
00:48:14,172 --> 00:48:16,092
And they sit down in deep contemplation.

471
00:48:16,494 --> 00:48:19,757
And they go to him and say, well, it's your wife.

472
00:48:20,257 --> 00:48:23,639
In the past life, she killed all these dogs.

473
00:48:23,701 --> 00:48:24,601
I can't remember what it was now.

474
00:48:24,782 --> 00:48:26,623
Dogs or something.

475
00:48:26,643 --> 00:48:28,905
So the only way it's going to move is to get rid of your wife, you see.

476
00:48:28,945 --> 00:48:29,945
So he throws her overboard.

477
00:48:30,327 --> 00:48:31,748
And of course, the ship moves on.

478
00:48:35,170 --> 00:48:36,871
There's one way to get rid of your wife.

479
00:48:37,371 --> 00:48:43,657
So you've got these stories coming from the scriptures of sort of moral retribution, you know.

480
00:48:44,998 --> 00:48:55,728
So there's the feeling that maybe to make sense of the whole karmic law, there has to be some equilibrium, some way in which things are worked out.

481
00:49:01,034 --> 00:49:02,195
So that's an intuitive thing.

482
00:49:02,735 --> 00:49:04,317
Either you've got it or you've not.

483
00:49:06,793 --> 00:49:27,199
And of course in terms of the whole process that we're in, which is about liberation, and about the, you might call it a sort of categorical imperative in the Buddha's teaching, that all beings are heading towards liberation, and they will make it.

484
00:49:27,617 --> 00:49:34,603
So there is in us this Buddha nature which is indestructible.

485
00:49:34,983 --> 00:49:35,585
That's the point.

486
00:49:36,125 --> 00:49:36,806
It's immortal.

487
00:49:37,005 --> 00:49:37,666
It doesn't die.

488
00:49:37,706 --> 00:49:38,347
It's not born.

489
00:49:39,327 --> 00:49:48,835
And so it will keep being reborn until it finds that it doesn't have to be reborn anymore and finds itself in a blissful place which we call Nibbana.

490
00:49:49,976 --> 00:49:56,222
And of course there are two descriptions of what that is.

491
00:49:56,302 --> 00:49:57,202
In Theravada

492
00:49:57,621 --> 00:50:00,405
The Self-Enlightened One just goes into Nibbana, full stop.

493
00:50:01,146 --> 00:50:02,027
Nothing more is said.

494
00:50:02,666 --> 00:50:06,731
But in the Mahayana, you're drawn out to help other beings.

495
00:50:06,751 --> 00:50:10,596
And therefore you reappear in your bliss body in different realms.

496
00:50:12,898 --> 00:50:23,730
So the whole idea of karma fits in with that basic idea that all beings are destined to be liberated one way or the other.

497
00:50:24,266 --> 00:50:34,380
So it's with this sort of rational argument, you see, it's not scientific, it's a rational argument, one might open up to the idea of rebirth.

498
00:50:35,001 --> 00:50:38,304
But having said all that, of course, it doesn't matter, does it?

499
00:50:38,666 --> 00:50:42,851
Because the Dharma works for us whether we believe it or not.

500
00:50:43,050 --> 00:50:46,596
So it's a case of really not coming to a conclusion.

501
00:50:48,635 --> 00:51:00,132
I quote here Bikobodi, the karmic process functions autonomously, without a supervisor or directly, entirely through its own intrinsic power of volitional action.

502
00:51:01,755 --> 00:51:07,605
So it's just the law of karma, there's no need for a god, there's no need for punishment, it just works itself out.

503
00:51:21,894 --> 00:51:46,688
there's a quote here from the Buddha which I'll end with the end of the world is to be seen known and reached by travelling that I do not say and yet I do not say that one makes an end of suffering without reaching the end of the world

504
00:51:47,376 --> 00:51:59,750
Rather, in this fathom-long body, with its consciousness and mind, I declare the world, the arising of the world, the ceasing of the world, and the way leading to the ceasing of the world.

505
00:52:01,751 --> 00:52:04,014
Just this is the end of suffering.

506
00:52:06,016 --> 00:52:16,168
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance, that they have not confused, and that through your practice you may be liberated from all suffering, sooner rather than later.

